1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","before 1221":"before 1221","1221":"1221","1296":"1296","about 1220":"about 1220","before 1239":"before 1239","Upton Warren, Worcestershire, England":"Upton Warren, Worcestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cokesey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Coakley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Coakley","meanings":["Irish (Cork): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Caochlaoich</b>, a patronymic from <i>Caochlaoch</i>, a personal name composed of the elements <i>caoch</i> ‘blind’ + <i>laoch</i> ‘warrior, hero’.","Irish: variant of <b>Cloughley</b>, possibly a shortened form of an unidentified Irish surname in <i>Mac-</i>."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":96,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":105,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh Cokesey was born as the son of Cokesey. He married Juliana le Poer about 1220. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 3 daughters. He died before 1239, and was buried in Upton Warren, Worcestershire, England."},"et":{"–before 1239":"–enne 1239","–1239":"–1239","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1221–1296":"1221–1296","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1239":"1239","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","before 1221":"enne 1221","1221":"1221","1296":"1296","about 1220":"umbes 1220","before 1239":"enne 1239","Upton Warren, Worcestershire, England":"Upton Warren, Worcestershire, England"},"fi":{"–before 1239":"–ennen vuotta 1239","–1239":"–1239","1200–Female":"1200–Kuollut","1221–1296":"1221–1296","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1239":"1239","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","before 1221":"ennen vuotta 1221","1221":"1221","1296":"1296","about 1220":"noin 1220","before 1239":"ennen vuotta 1239","Upton Warren, Worcestershire, England":"Upton Warren, Worcestershire, England"},"fr":{"–before 1239":"–avant 1239","–1239":"–1239","1200–Female":"1200–Décédée","1221–1296":"1221–1296","–Female":"Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1239":"1239","1215":"